Probabilistic Neuro-Symbolic Runtime Verification for Safe Pixel-Based Autonomous Agents

Candidate: ouadi Maakoul 


Date: October 2026

---

Abstract

Autonomous agents that interact with graphical user interfaces (GUIs) via pixel observations are increasingly deployed in critical domains such as finance, healthcare, and enterprise IT. These agents rely on neural perception models to map raw pixels to symbolic states, but perception is inherently uncertain and can lead to catastrophic actions (e.g., deleting files, initiating unauthorized transactions). Existing safety mechanisms either ignore perception uncertainty or use heuristic guards that lack formal guarantees.

This thesis develops a Probabilistic Neuro-Symbolic Runtime Verification Framework that provides rigorous safety guarantees despite uncertain perception. We formalize the problem as a Partially Observable Markov Decision Process with a probabilistic perception layer. We introduce UI-PTL (User Interface Probabilistic Temporal Logic), a temporal logic that extends Linear Temporal Logic with probabilistic operators to express safety requirements over uncertain UI states. We provide a measure‑theoretic semantics for UI-PTL that accounts for the interval‑valued nature of neural perception. We design a probabilistic shield that, at runtime, computes a guaranteed upper bound on the probability of violating a given safety property, using interval bound propagation (IBP) to abstract the neural perception model and SMT solving to evaluate the specification. We incorporate Fréchet–Hoeffding bounds to capture dependencies between UI elements, reducing conservatism. We also integrate control barrier certificates to provide infinite‑horizon safety guarantees. We prove that the shield is sound (it never underestimates risk), that its latency is bounded under realistic parametric assumptions, and that the utility loss due to shielding is bounded by the width of the perception abstraction intervals, establishing a direct link between perception quality and agent productivity. The framework is purely mathematical and provides a foundation for building verifiably safe autonomous agents.

