Chapter 2: Preliminaries

We establish the notation and background concepts used throughout the thesis.

2.1 Notation

· \mathbb{N} denotes natural numbers, \mathbb{R} real numbers.
· Vectors are denoted in bold, e.g., \mathbf{x}.
· \|\cdot\|_p denotes the L_p norm.
· \mathcal{P}(X) denotes the set of probability distributions over a set X.

2.2 UI State Space

A graphical user interface can be described as a set of interactive elements. We define a symbolic UI state as a structured object.

Definition 2.1 (UI Element). A UI element is a tuple e = (\text{type}, \text{position}, \text{text}, \text{color}, \text{enabled}) where:

· \text{type} \in \{\text{button}, \text{textfield}, \text{checkbox}, \text{menu}, \dots\}.
· \text{position} \in \mathbb{R}^2 (bounding box or coordinates).
· \text{text} \in \Sigma^* (a string over some alphabet).
· \text{color} \in \mathbb{R}^3 (RGB values).
· \text{enabled} \in \{\text{true}, \text{false}\}.

A symbolic UI state z is a finite set of UI elements.

Definition 2.2 (Action Space). An action a \in \mathcal{A} is a pair (\text{type}, \text{target}) where \text{type} \in \{\text{click}, \text{type}, \text{scroll}, \text{wait}\} and \text{target} is either a reference to a UI element (e.g., by position or identifier) or a string for typing.

2.3 Probabilistic Perception

The agent observes a pixel screenshot x \in \mathcal{X}. A perception model is a function that maps x to a distribution over symbolic states. In practice, this is often a neural network that outputs class probabilities for each element’s attributes.

Definition 2.3 (Perception Distribution). Let \mathcal{P}_\theta: \mathcal{X} \to \mathcal{P}(\mathcal{Z}) be a perception model parameterized by \theta. For a given observation x, we denote the probability of a symbolic state z as P_\theta(z \mid x).

We make the following assumption, which is standard in verification of neural networks:

Assumption 2.1 (Bounded Input Domain). The input space \mathcal{X} is bounded: \mathcal{X} \subset [0,1]^{H \times W \times 3}. Furthermore, the perception model \mathcal{P}_\theta is Lipschitz continuous with respect to the input, i.e., there exists L > 0 such that for all x_1, x_2 \in \mathcal{X},

\| \mathcal{P}_\theta(x_1) - \mathcal{P}_\theta(x_2) \|_\infty \le L \|x_1 - x_2\|_\infty.

2.4 Linear Temporal Logic (LTL)

We recall the syntax and semantics of LTL over a set of atomic propositions AP.

Definition 2.4 (LTL Syntax). Formulas \phi are defined by:

\phi ::= p \mid \neg \phi \mid \phi \land \phi \mid \bigcirc \phi \mid \phi \mathcal{U} \phi

where p \in AP. Additional operators \Diamond \phi \equiv \text{true} \mathcal{U} \phi (eventually) and \Box \phi \equiv \neg \Diamond \neg \phi (always) are derived.

Definition 2.5 (LTL Semantics). Given an infinite trace \sigma = \sigma_0, \sigma_1, \dots where each \sigma_i is a set of atomic propositions, the satisfaction relation \sigma, i \models \phi is defined inductively. We omit the standard details.

2.5 Safety Specifications

A safety specification is a property that forbids certain bad prefixes. In LTL, many safety properties can be expressed as \Box \psi where \psi is a propositional formula. However, we need to handle probabilities over atomic propositions that are themselves uncertain.

