Chapter 3: Mathematical Framework

This chapter formalizes the agent’s environment as a POMDP with a probabilistic perception layer, defines UI-PTL with its measure‑theoretic semantics, and introduces the tools needed for runtime verification.

3.1 Pixel‑Based POMDP

Definition 3.1 (Pixel‑POMDP). A Pixel‑POMDP is a tuple \mathcal{M} = \langle \mathcal{X}, \mathcal{Z}, \mathcal{A}, T, R, \Omega, \gamma \rangle where:

· \mathcal{X} is the set of pixel observations (images).
· \mathcal{Z} is the set of symbolic states (UI element sets).
· \mathcal{A} is the set of actions.
· T: \mathcal{Z} \times \mathcal{A} \to \mathcal{P}(\mathcal{Z}) is the transition function, giving the distribution over next symbolic states given current symbolic state and action.
· R: \mathcal{Z} \times \mathcal{A} \to \mathbb{R} is the reward function (not used in safety verification but relevant for performance).
· \Omega: \mathcal{Z} \to \mathcal{P}(\mathcal{X}) is the observation function, describing the distribution over pixel observations given a symbolic state.
· \gamma \in [0,1) is the discount factor.

The agent does not observe z_t directly. Instead, it receives an observation x_t and uses a perception model to form a belief over z_t. We model the perception model separately, as a learned component.

Definition 3.2 (Perception‑Augmented POMDP). We augment the Pixel‑POMDP with a perception model \mathcal{P}_\theta: \mathcal{X} \to \mathcal{P}(\mathcal{Z}). The agent’s belief at time t is then given by:

b_t(z) = \sum_{x} P(z \mid x) \cdot \Omega(x \mid z_t) \quad \text{(marginalized)}.

For safety verification, we only need the distribution over z_t conditioned on the current observation x_t, i.e., P(z_t \mid x_t). This is precisely the output of the perception model.

3.2 UI Probabilistic Temporal Logic (UI-PTL)

To specify safety under uncertainty, we extend LTL with a probabilistic operator that quantifies over the perception distribution.

Definition 3.3 (UI-PTL Syntax). Let AP be a set of atomic propositions, where each p \in AP is a predicate over the current symbolic state z and action a (e.g., “the focused button’s label is ‘Delete’”). UI-PTL formulas are defined by:

\phi ::= p \mid \neg \phi \mid \phi \land \phi \mid \bigcirc \phi \mid \phi \mathcal{U} \phi \mid \mathbb{P}_{\sim \lambda}(\phi)

where \sim \in \{<, \le, \ge, >\} and \lambda \in [0,1].

3.2.1 Measure‑Theoretic Semantics

Because perception yields only intervals on atomic propositions, we define satisfaction in terms of a belief set \mathcal{B}_t containing all joint distributions consistent with the IBP‑derived intervals.

Definition 3.4 (Consistent Distribution Set). For a given observation x_t, let p_1, \dots, p_k be the atomic propositions in the formula. For each p_i, the IBP module provides an interval [\underline{p}_i, \overline{p}_i] such that the true probability \mathbb{P}(p_i \mid x_t) lies in that interval. The set of consistent distributions \mathcal{B}_t is defined as:

\mathcal{B}_t = \left\{ Q \in \mathcal{P}(\mathcal{Z}) \;\middle|\; \forall i,\; \underline{p}_i \le Q(\{z : p_i(z) \text{ true}\}) \le \overline{p}_i \right\}.

Definition 3.5 (Satisfaction of Probabilistic Operator). For a UI-PTL formula \mathbb{P}_{\sim \lambda}(\psi) and a trace \sigma = (z_0, a_0), (z_1, a_1), \dots, we say that \sigma, t \models \mathbb{P}_{\sim \lambda}(\psi) if and only if for all distributions Q \in \mathcal{B}_t (robust satisfaction):

Q\big( \{z_t : \sigma, t \models \psi \text{ under deterministic semantics}\} \big) \sim \lambda.

That is, the probability of \psi holding (given the current perception uncertainty) satisfies the bound for every distribution consistent with the intervals.

This robust interpretation ensures that the shield’s decision is sound: if the specification is satisfied under the robust semantics, then no matter which actual distribution generated the observation, the safety property holds with the required probability.

3.3 Probabilistic Dependency Modeling

A major limitation of naive interval abstraction is the inability to capture correlations between atomic propositions. In a UI, the truth values of “button labeled ‘Delete’ is present” and “confirmation dialog is visible” are highly correlated. Ignoring this leads to overly conservative risk estimates.

Definition 3.6 (Fréchet–Hoeffding Bounds). For a set of atomic propositions p_1,\dots,p_k with marginal probabilities q_i \in [\underline{p}_i, \overline{p}_i], the joint probability of any conjunction \bigwedge_{i \in I} p_i \land \bigwedge_{j \notin I} \neg p_j is bounded by:

\max\left(0, \sum_{i \in I} q_i - (|I|-1)\right) \le \mathbb{P}\big(\bigwedge_{i \in I} p_i\big) \le \min_{i \in I} q_i.

For general Boolean formulas, the probability can be bounded using the principle of inclusion–exclusion with these bounds. This yields a linear programming relaxation that respects dependencies without requiring the full joint distribution.

Corollary 3.1 (SMT Encoding with Dependency Bounds). The constraints derived from Fréchet–Hoeffding bounds are linear in the marginal probabilities q_i. Therefore, the SMT encoding of a UI-PTL safety property can be expressed as a linear program over the intervals [\underline{p}_i, \overline{p}_i].

3.4 Interval Bound Propagation with Tightness

We adopt IBP as the abstraction method. To improve precision, we incorporate the following refinement:

Lemma 3.1 (Softmax Tightness). For a neural network outputting logits \ell_1,\dots,\ell_m, with intervals [\underline{\ell}_i, \overline{\ell}_i], the resulting probability interval for class j is:

\underline{p}_j = \frac{e^{\underline{\ell}_j}}{e^{\underline{\ell}_j} + \sum_{i \neq j} e^{\overline{\ell}_i}}, \quad \overline{p}_j = \frac{e^{\overline{\ell}_j}}{e^{\overline{\ell}_j} + \sum_{i \neq j} e^{\underline{\ell}_i}}.

These bounds are optimal (i.e., the tightest possible) for the given logit intervals.

Proof. The softmax function is monotone in each logit: increasing \ell_j increases p_j and decreases all others. Hence the extreme values occur at the extremes of the logit intervals. \square

3.5 Barrier Certificates for Infinite Horizon

To avoid the “finite horizon” limitation, we incorporate the concept of control barrier functions (CBFs) into the safety specification.

Definition 3.7 (Safety Set). Let \mathcal{S} \subseteq \mathcal{Z} be the set of symbolic states that are considered safe. We assume \mathcal{S} is defined by a set of linear inequalities over UI element attributes.

Definition 3.8 (Discrete‑Time Control Barrier Function). A function h: \mathcal{Z} \to \mathbb{R} is a discrete‑time CBF for the system if there exists \alpha \in [0,1) such that for all states z \in \mathcal{S},

h(z) \ge 0,

and for every admissible action a, the expected next state satisfies:

\mathbb{E}[h(z') \mid z,a] \ge \alpha \, h(z).

Theorem 3.1 (Forward Invariance). If there exists a CBF h with \alpha \in [0,1), then the set \{z \mid h(z) \ge 0\} is forward invariant under any policy that respects the inequality. In particular, starting from a safe state, the system remains safe forever.

Proof. Standard in the CBF literature. \square

In our shield, we can pre‑compute a CBF for the environment dynamics (which are known from the UI semantics). At runtime, we check whether the proposed action satisfies \mathbb{E}[h(z') \mid z,a] \ge \alpha h(z) under the current perception distribution. This gives an infinite‑horizon safety guarantee.

