Chapter 7: Conclusion

This thesis has presented a comprehensive mathematical framework for ensuring the safety of pixel‑based autonomous agents under perception uncertainty. We introduced UI-PTL, a temporal logic for specifying safety properties with probabilistic constraints, and provided a measure‑theoretic semantics that accounts for interval‑valued perception. We designed a neuro‑symbolic runtime verification architecture that combines interval bound propagation with SMT solving, incorporating Fréchet–Hoeffding bounds to capture dependencies and control barrier certificates for infinite‑horizon safety. We proved soundness, stability under perturbations, parametric latency bounds, and—crucially—a utility loss bound that links the tightness of perception abstraction directly to agent productivity.

The proposed shield acts as an epistemic safety layer—a verifiable wrapper that can be placed around any agent, transforming an unreliable perception‑action loop into a system with formal risk guarantees. By establishing that “tighter intervals lead to higher utility,” we provide a mathematical incentive for developing more precise and stable perception models. This work lays the groundwork for deploying autonomous agents in safety‑critical domains, where the cost of a mistake is too high to rely on heuristics.

Future work will focus on refining the probabilistic reasoning to reduce conservatism, extending the framework to temporal properties, and integrating the shield with agent training to achieve both safety and high performance.

