Appendix: Detailed Proofs

A.1 UI-PTL Satisfaction under Joint Uncertainty (Expanded)

We provide the full measure‑theoretic definition of satisfaction for UI-PTL.

Definition A.1 (Belief Set). Given an observation x_t and atomic propositions p_1,\dots,p_k, let \mathcal{B}_t be the set of all probability distributions Q on \mathcal{Z} such that for each i,

\underline{p}_i \le Q(\{z : p_i(z) \text{ true}\}) \le \overline{p}_i.

Definition A.2 (Satisfaction of UI-PTL). For a trace \sigma = (z_0, a_0), (z_1, a_1), \dots and time t, we define:

· For an atomic proposition p, \sigma, t \models p iff p(z_t, a_t) holds in the usual deterministic sense.
· Boolean and temporal operators follow standard LTL semantics.
· For \mathbb{P}_{\sim \lambda}(\psi):
  \sigma, t \models \mathbb{P}_{\sim \lambda}(\psi) \iff \forall Q \in \mathcal{B}_t,\; Q\big( \{z : (\sigma[t \mapsto z], t) \models \psi\} \big) \sim \lambda,
  where \sigma[t \mapsto z] denotes the trace with the state at time t replaced by z.

A.2 Soundness of the SMT Encoding – Full Proof

Theorem A.1 (Soundness). Let \hat{p} be the value obtained by solving the linear program described in Algorithm 4.1. Then for the true perception distribution P(z \mid x_t), the violation probability p_{\text{viol}} = P(\{z : \neg \psi(z,a_t)\}) satisfies p_{\text{viol}} \le \hat{p}.

Proof.

1. By Lemma 4.1, the true marginal probabilities q_i^* = P(p_i \mid x_t) satisfy l_i \le q_i^* \le u_i.
2. The Fréchet–Hoeffding bounds are valid for any joint distribution with these marginals, so the true joint distribution lies in the convex polytope \mathcal{H} defined by the linear constraints.
3. The dangerous condition \neg \psi is a Boolean function of the atomic propositions. Its probability can be expressed as a linear combination of probabilities of conjunctions (e.g., by converting to disjunctive normal form). The linear program LP maximizes this probability over \mathcal{H} using the linear bounds for conjunctions. Therefore, the true probability p_{\text{viol}} is at most the maximum over \mathcal{H}, i.e., \hat{p} \ge p_{\text{viol}}. \square

A.3 Tightness Improvement with Fréchet–Hoeffding Bounds

The use of Fréchet–Hoeffding bounds reduces conservatism compared to the union bound. For a conjunction p_1 \land p_2, the union bound would give P(p_1 \land p_2) \le \min(q_1, q_2), which is the same as the upper Fréchet bound, but the lower bound \max(0, q_1+q_2-1) provides a non‑trivial bound that prevents over‑estimation of risk when q_1 and q_2 are both high. In the context of the dangerous condition p_1 \land \neg p_2, the Fréchet lower bound gives a tighter estimate of the actual probability.

